1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
 Thank you, team. Church, you can go ahead and grab a seat.

2
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:19,000
 Okay, so this is going to be interesting. I haven't really tried it out yet. It only works in my head.

3
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:27,000
 But I want to tell you guys something about me, without showing you the Viha brand, because I'm not necessarily endorsing them.

4
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:38,000
 So, I am a bit of a modified hipster, okay? So, it's just truth. I'm a complete hipster. I'm wearing the hipster beanie.

5
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:42,000
 I like to do hipster things, and I've just given into the reality that I'm a hipster.

6
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:46,000
 And so, one of the things I want to share with you guys is about my hipsterness, something you might not know about me.

7
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:51,000
 Most people have iPhones, and they take pictures with their iPhones.

8
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:58,000
 And, you know, if you're a bit more fancy or more professional, you have a digital camera. You take pictures with your digital camera.

9
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:05,000
 Me being a hipster means that I don't just use digital cameras, but I like film cameras, okay?

10
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:11,000
 Film isn't really a thing to do, because since the 1990s, digital's become a thing.

11
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:17,000
 But I like to carry around film cameras. I know almost everything about film cameras and every film.

12
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:21,000
 This is Portra 400, one of the best films you can actually buy for medium format.

13
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:25,000
 I would know this because I've researched everything. I've watched every YouTube video.

14
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:31,000
 This is Ultramax 400, also a 400-speed film. This is my personal favorite. It's actually quite cheap as well.

15
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:35,000
 You can buy the three-pack all at the same time. This is the way to go. I'm obsessed with this.

16
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:41,000
 So, like I said, I've watched every video on Instagram. You know, I'm only 35, so I have Instagram.

17
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:48,000
 Just saying, in case you don't know. On Instagram, I have folders saved with all my favorite images.

18
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:54,000
 Some of my favorite images are taken on films called Lumography. This is Lumography 400.

19
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:58,000
 It's a bit cheaper than the Kodak option, because Kodak's quite expensive.

20
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:04,000
 And then if you're super hipster, you can also shoot in black and white, because you don't need color when you have such great composition skills, right?

21
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:13,000
 So, I also have Ilford 100 and XP 200, and we have one more film in here.

22
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:18,000
 This is a new bad boy that I have become obsessed with. Kodak just released it recently.

23
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:26,000
 This is Kodacolor 200. Now, from all the things I've read online, it's pretty much the same film that's already existed.

24
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:31,000
 They just rebranded it. But I'm the sucker who went out and bought it, because it's more expensive, and I think it shoots nicer.

25
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:41,000
 But I've read every possible blog, I've seen every video, I've filled my Instagram folder with all the things to know about film photography.

26
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:49,000
 I've watched every YouTube video, the long ones, the short ones. I know so, so much about film photography.

27
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:52,000
 If that one doesn't resonate with you, I'll try another one.

28
00:02:52,000 --> 00:03:04,000
 My second big favorite hobby is cooking, believe it or not. I also, on Instagram, have folders just filled with recipes.

29
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:12,000
 Korean recipes, because I'm obsessed with Korean food. I know the right kimchi to buy, I know the right noodles, I know the right soybean paste.

30
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:18,000
 I've got it all figured out. I've written it down. There's lots of things on here, and you can take a photo of this if you need.

31
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:22,000
 If you want some good recipes, y'all, this is good stuff.

32
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:29,000
 But I follow all the famous people who put out these super simple recipes to follow throughout your week, so you can make dinner really easily.

33
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:34,000
 I've acquired so much of this stuff. I have it down. I've got these folders filled.

34
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:42,000
 But if I'm honest, these folders are filled, but I've probably only made one of these recipes.

35
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:49,000
 Just being honest, I've accumulated all the information on it. I've got it saved. I'm even so prepared.

36
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:55,000
 I have an Excel sheet with all the different information on it in case I don't want photos, but I want clear steps.

37
00:03:55,000 --> 00:04:04,000
 I've gathered everything I need to know about photography and about cooking in order to be a good cook and in order to take good photos.

38
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:12,000
 But I think we all know that just because you have the information on a thing, just because I have the camera and all the different film,

39
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:21,000
 just because my Instagram is full of recipes I'll never use doesn't make me necessarily good at that thing.

40
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:26,000
 Composition in photography is more than liking a couple things on Instagram.

41
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:34,000
 Being a good cook, preparing foods for your family, and learning all these different meals goes beyond clicking Save to Folder.

42
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:42,000
 That's actually the easy thing, right? It doesn't take much work, just a quick thumb exercise to click Save to Folder.

43
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:47,000
 What is the name of this folder? Must-try recipes. Okay, cool. Save it to your must-try recipes.

44
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:51,000
 But there is a difference, and I guess that's what I want to draw our attention to.

45
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:59,000
 There is a difference between knowing and knowing about. I know a lot about recipes.

46
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:06,000
 To be fair, I also know a lot about cooking because I do cook a lot, and I do take a lot of photos on my film camera.

47
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:11,000
 But there is a difference between understanding a thing and knowing it and having the information and talking about it

48
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:17,000
 and accumulating knowledge about it and actually knowing the thing itself.

49
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:23,000
 We've been sitting here in this series for the past couple of weeks on the idea of waiting.

50
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:26,000
 And let's be honest. It doesn't matter how many sermons are preached on waiting.

51
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:30,000
 It doesn't matter how great the PowerPoints are or how great the props are.

52
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:36,000
 Waiting is still hard. It still creates tension in us.

53
00:05:36,000 --> 00:05:47,000
 And no matter how good we feel like this season might be, it still requires a daily commitment to submit ourselves to that waiting process

54
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:51,000
 and to control our emotions and to not spiral.

55
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:55,000
 Is anyone here guilty of the temptation to spiral when you're waiting?

56
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:57,000
 Is that just me? Anyone that starts to spiral?

57
00:05:57,000 --> 00:05:59,000
 What if it doesn't happen? What if the worst-case scenario takes place?

58
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:02,000
 What if everything goes downhill? Yeah, a few of us? Four of us? Cool.

59
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:06,000
 You guys can join me at the prayer line early. Okay, cool, cool. There's a few of you.

60
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:15,000
 But did you know that waiting well is actually fueled by a couple of components, a couple of ideas?

61
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:19,000
 There are some really important, crucial ideas that everything hinges on,

62
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:26,000
 that if we were to understand them in our waiting, would actually produce something for us in our waiting.

63
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:30,000
 Not just that we're waiting for a thing, but if we understood these components,

64
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:36,000
 if we were to take in these concepts, we would understand how to wait well with hope.

65
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:41,000
 We would learn how to wait well regardless of temptation to spiral.

66
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:53,000
 That it would activate this active anticipation of change that would produce a current good in us and a future good as well.

67
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:57,000
 Pastor Andrew says regularly that waiting is a gift.

68
00:06:57,000 --> 00:07:02,000
 And the first time I remember myself and the creative team, when we heard this, we're like, "What?

69
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:04,000
 Why is waiting a gift? That just sounds so ugh."

70
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:10,000
 But the more you think about it, and as we look at it today, we'll see that there actually is a gift,

71
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:17,000
 a couple of gifts to be found in the waiting season, listen to this, beyond what you're waiting for.

72
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:24,000
 God has in planned for us, not just to resolve the tension that we are waiting within,

73
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:31,000
 but to give us things, give us gifts in order to impact and change us.

74
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:34,000
 And so we're going to be part in Psalm 27.

75
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:39,000
 We've been here for the entire series, looking this week at verses 7 through 12.

76
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:40,000
 Let me read it for us.

77
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:45,000
 It says this, "Hear, O Lord, when I cry aloud.

78
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:48,000
 Be gracious to me and answer me.

79
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:49,000
 You have said, 'Seek my face.'

80
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:53,000
 My heart says to you, 'Your face, Lord, do I seek.'

81
00:07:53,000 --> 00:07:55,000
 Hide not your face from me.

82
00:07:55,000 --> 00:07:58,000
 Turn not your servants away in anger.

83
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:01,000
 O you who have been my help, cast me not off.

84
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:04,000
 Forsake me not, O God of my salvation.

85
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:10,000
 For my father and my mother have forsaken me, but the Lord will take me in.

86
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:16,000
 So teach me your ways, O Lord, and lead me on a level path because of my enemies.

87
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:19,000
 Give me not up to the will of my adversaries.

88
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:23,000
 For false witnesses have risen against me, and they breathe out violence."

89
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:25,000
 Let me pray.

90
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:32,000
 God, we open your word, and we just ask, Holy Spirit, that you--

91
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:37,000
 what is said about you is that you help us understand what is written,

92
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:38,000
 that you give us wisdom.

93
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:43,000
 So we ask that you, in this moment, as we look at your word, would be our wisdom,

94
00:08:43,000 --> 00:08:46,000
 would show us what it is that you want us to see.

95
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:51,000
 We submit ourselves and humble ourselves to be under your word today.

96
00:08:51,000 --> 00:08:53,000
 Would you speak in Jesus' name?

97
00:08:53,000 --> 00:08:55,000
 Amen.

98
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:59,000
 So if you're familiar with what we've talked about so far, verses 1 through 6,

99
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:02,000
 David's tone has changed a little bit.

100
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:06,000
 By the time we get to verse 7, something is different in how he's speaking.

101
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:11,000
 In the first six verses, the way he's talking is very faith-filled.

102
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:13,000
 It's very about God.

103
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:17,000
 He's using this head knowledge that he's acquired about God.

104
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:21,000
 He's speaking about things that he has heard or that he knows,

105
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:25,000
 things that he understands, facts and things that he knows about God.

106
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:27,000
 He's saying things like, "God is my light and my salvation.

107
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:28,000
 Whom shall I fear?"

108
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:33,000
 He's talking about the things of God that he knows, information and understanding.

109
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:35,000
 So he's pretty much telling himself, "It's going to be okay.

110
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:36,000
 I don't need to worry.

111
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:37,000
 It's fine.

112
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:38,000
 Everything's fine.

113
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:39,000
 Nothing to worry about.

114
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:40,000
 It's fine.

115
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:41,000
 God is my light and my salvation.

116
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:42,000
 Whom shall I fear?

117
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:43,000
 It doesn't matter how long I'm waiting.

118
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:45,000
 It doesn't matter how much trouble I'm in.

119
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:46,000
 God is with me."

120
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:49,000
 He's spouting out this theology that is meant to help him.

121
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:53,000
 And a lot of us find ourselves in that place as well.

122
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:57,000
 He's convincing himself, giving himself the strength he needs

123
00:09:57,000 --> 00:10:02,000
 by reciting what he knows about God.

124
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:06,000
 But something different changes in verse 7.

125
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:10,000
 He adds a new component to the way that he engages.

126
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:13,000
 David takes it further.

127
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:18,000
 And this new thing he does is something I think we can all miss sometimes in our

128
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:20,000
 seasons of waiting.

129
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:27,000
 He stops talking about God, and he starts talking to God.

130
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:28,000
 Sit with that for a minute.

131
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:31,000
 He stops talking about all the things and all the attributes he knows about God,

132
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:33,000
 and he starts talking to God.

133
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:37,000
 A subtle difference, but it has massive implications.

134
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:42,000
 You could say he stops theologizing and he starts praying,

135
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:43,000
 which seems a bit silly.

136
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:45,000
 Like, how is he not praying already?

137
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:49,000
 So he turns his attention to God, and he addresses him clearly.

138
00:10:49,000 --> 00:10:53,000
 He says, "Hear, O Lord, when I cry aloud.

139
00:10:53,000 --> 00:10:55,000
 Be gracious to me and answer me.

140
00:10:55,000 --> 00:10:57,000
 You have said, 'Seek my face.'"

141
00:10:57,000 --> 00:11:00,000
 He's like, "God, hear me.

142
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:03,000
 This isn't easy.

143
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:04,000
 God, hear me.

144
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:05,000
 I'm crying out to you.

145
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:09,000
 What I'm feeling now in this moment isn't enjoyable."

146
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:11,000
 He cries out to God.

147
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:14,000
 He's honest before God.

148
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:19,000
 The idea of crying out is so unique because David is the king, right?

149
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:21,000
 He's the king of a nation that's doing really well.

150
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:25,000
 And the way that it's set up is that the king is here, and he has prophets,

151
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:26,000
 and he has priests.

152
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:28,000
 And if he needs someone to go to God on his behalf,

153
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:31,000
 he has a priest to go to God on his behalf.

154
00:11:31,000 --> 00:11:35,000
 But the king is taking this humble position of vulnerability,

155
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:39,000
 and he's crying out to God.

156
00:11:39,000 --> 00:11:44,000
 When was the last time you cried out to God?

157
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:49,000
 When was the last time you were like, "God, I hate waiting?

158
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:52,000
 God, waiting isn't producing what I want.

159
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:56,000
 Everyone else is getting what they want, but I haven't gotten mine yet.

160
00:11:56,000 --> 00:12:00,000
 God, everything I see around me tells me it's never going to work out.

161
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:05,000
 God, I'm so close to spiraling again."

162
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:09,000
 When was the last time you cried out to God?

163
00:12:09,000 --> 00:12:12,000
 David gets real with God.

164
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:16,000
 And I think sometimes as Christians we can think we just need to put the good

165
00:12:16,000 --> 00:12:17,000
 words together.

166
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:18,000
 "He is my rock.

167
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:19,000
 He is my salvation.

168
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:20,000
 He is my strength."

169
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:24,000
 Yes, that's true, but he also is there to hear you.

170
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:27,000
 He also wants to hear how your heart is broken.

171
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:33,000
 There's something about crying out to God that David sees in this section.

172
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:36,000
 It's more than telling yourself how faithful God is.

173
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:38,000
 It's more than proclaiming all the promises,

174
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:40,000
 but it's telling God that your heart hurts,

175
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:43,000
 and it's telling God that you're broken over the situation,

176
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:46,000
 that it's gripping your emotions, that you fear,

177
00:12:46,000 --> 00:12:49,000
 and that you feel like you might fail.

178
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:53,000
 It's that honesty that crying out calls us to do.

179
00:12:53,000 --> 00:13:02,000
 So when was the last time you cried out to God?

180
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:07,000
 David knows something in this psalm that we'll see across other psalms and other

181
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:14,000
 passages in Scripture, that we have to let our theology lead to prayer,

182
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:18,000
 that when we're vulnerable before God, something happens.

183
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:25,000
 In our waiting, we need our vulnerability before God.

184
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:28,000
 When we cry out to God, we express this vulnerability,

185
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:31,000
 and in that vulnerability, something is produced.

186
00:13:31,000 --> 00:13:33,000
 It's called intimacy.

187
00:13:33,000 --> 00:13:37,000
 See, when we cry out to God, when we pour our hearts out to God,

188
00:13:37,000 --> 00:13:39,000
 something happens.

189
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:41,000
 God hears you.

190
00:13:41,000 --> 00:13:43,000
 There's so many Scriptures.

191
00:13:43,000 --> 00:13:46,000
 I love the word he uses, he cries out.

192
00:13:46,000 --> 00:13:49,000
 The word cry is so important because so many times God would say,

193
00:13:49,000 --> 00:13:55,000
 "From heaven, I have heard the cry of my people."

194
00:13:55,000 --> 00:13:59,000
 But if we never cry, how is he going to hear us?

195
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:03,000
 He doesn't say, "I've heard the resolve of your theology."

196
00:14:03,000 --> 00:14:06,000
 He says, "I've heard the cry of my people,

197
00:14:06,000 --> 00:14:11,000
 and I have come down to liberate, to free, to be with them."

198
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:16,000
 Church, when was the last time we cried out to God?

199
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:20,000
 Could it be that in this vulnerability of crying out to God,

200
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:26,000
 we find that God draws himself to us?

201
00:14:26,000 --> 00:14:29,000
 There's a verse that says -- actually, I'll get through in a minute.

202
00:14:29,000 --> 00:14:33,000
 Let me not go too fast.

203
00:14:33,000 --> 00:14:35,000
 Vulnerability leads to this.

204
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:42,000
 He says, "You have said, 'Seek my face.'

205
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:45,000
 My heart says to you, 'Your face, Lord, I do seek.'"

206
00:14:45,000 --> 00:14:46,000
 So what is happening in this verse?

207
00:14:46,000 --> 00:14:48,000
 It's such a weird thing to say.

208
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:49,000
 He's being vulnerable.

209
00:14:49,000 --> 00:14:51,000
 He's saying, "I'm crying out," and God is saying, "Seek my face."

210
00:14:51,000 --> 00:14:53,000
 He says, "Okay, I'm going to seek your face."

211
00:14:53,000 --> 00:14:55,000
 What is he talking about?

212
00:14:55,000 --> 00:15:00,000
 What is this idea of face-seeking?

213
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:06,000
 God's not asking for Christian jargon, but he's asking for vulnerability,

214
00:15:06,000 --> 00:15:10,000
 and vulnerability has something to do with seeking God's face.

215
00:15:10,000 --> 00:15:14,000
 To seek his face is to seek his countenance, to understand what he's about.

216
00:15:14,000 --> 00:15:16,000
 And I was looking up the word "countenance."

217
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:19,000
 One of the things I saw is the ability to understand what someone's doing

218
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:22,000
 without them even saying anything.

219
00:15:22,000 --> 00:15:26,000
 It's this intimacy, this closeness, where God doesn't have to speak,

220
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:29,000
 but I can know his heart because I've been with him.

221
00:15:29,000 --> 00:15:34,000
 To seek his face is to know him personally, not just what Pastor Andrew

222
00:15:34,000 --> 00:15:39,000
 or Pastor Carla or Pastor Ellison or Pastor Promise has said about God,

223
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:40,000
 because we can be good at that.

224
00:15:40,000 --> 00:15:45,000
 We can quote what the preacher says, but if we seek his face ourselves,

225
00:15:45,000 --> 00:15:50,000
 we can then know who he truly is.

226
00:15:50,000 --> 00:15:55,000
 When we cry out to God, we are invited to seek his face, to know him,

227
00:15:55,000 --> 00:15:58,000
 to come closer to him.

228
00:15:58,000 --> 00:16:00,000
 Do you see what God is doing here?

229
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:08,000
 Our vulnerability is an invitation to intimacy with God, to really knowing him.

230
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:12,000
 That's the reason that James would tell us that if we draw near to him,

231
00:16:12,000 --> 00:16:15,000
 he will draw near to us.

232
00:16:15,000 --> 00:16:18,000
 Like in this season of waiting, I think for a lot of us,

233
00:16:18,000 --> 00:16:22,000
 we think that the longer we wait, the further God is,

234
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:24,000
 but potentially we have that backwards.

235
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:27,000
 Because if we were to cry out, if we were to be vulnerable,

236
00:16:27,000 --> 00:16:32,000
 allow that invitation of intimacy to exist, perhaps that drawing near to him,

237
00:16:32,000 --> 00:16:36,000
 he would draw near to us, and we would find that even in our waiting,

238
00:16:36,000 --> 00:16:38,000
 God's not distant.

239
00:16:38,000 --> 00:16:40,000
 God's not far away.

240
00:16:40,000 --> 00:16:45,000
 He's so much closer than we realize.

241
00:16:45,000 --> 00:16:53,000
 And we need to know him for ourselves, and that's what this does for us.

242
00:16:53,000 --> 00:17:00,000
 Psalm 34 would say this, "The Lord draws near to the brokenhearted."

243
00:17:00,000 --> 00:17:08,000
 So let me just -- if you are currently waiting, and it stings,

244
00:17:08,000 --> 00:17:13,000
 and you're frustrated, and you're -- if you're disappointed,

245
00:17:13,000 --> 00:17:15,000
 God draws near to that.

246
00:17:15,000 --> 00:17:18,000
 God doesn't shoo that away.

247
00:17:18,000 --> 00:17:20,000
 If you're anxious, and you're struggling,

248
00:17:20,000 --> 00:17:25,000
 and you just can't make it make sense, and you're feeling all the feels,

249
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:28,000
 God draws near to that.

250
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:29,000
 He doesn't run away from that.

251
00:17:29,000 --> 00:17:30,000
 That doesn't scare him.

252
00:17:30,000 --> 00:17:33,000
 He doesn't need you to have all your stuff together.

253
00:17:33,000 --> 00:17:38,000
 God draws near to the brokenhearted.

254
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:44,000
 The intimacy of God, knowing him, is a byproduct of crying out to him.

255
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:50,000
 Because when we know the face of God, it's going to impact how we wait.

256
00:17:50,000 --> 00:17:54,000
 And so it's deeply important that we know who he is,

257
00:17:54,000 --> 00:17:59,000
 not just what we feel in the moment, which oftentimes sounds louder

258
00:17:59,000 --> 00:18:04,000
 and is more clear, but it's important that we know who he is

259
00:18:04,000 --> 00:18:06,000
 and what is true about him.

260
00:18:06,000 --> 00:18:08,000
 We need to know for ourselves.

261
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:11,000
 And it's only from this posture of intimacy that we're able to understand

262
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:15,000
 what David is describing in the next two verses in verses 9 and 10.

263
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:17,000
 He says this, "Hide not your face from me.

264
00:18:17,000 --> 00:18:19,000
 Turn not your servants away in anger.

265
00:18:19,000 --> 00:18:22,000
 Oh, you who have been my help, cast me not off.

266
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:23,000
 Forsake me not.

267
00:18:23,000 --> 00:18:25,000
 Oh, God, my salvation.

268
00:18:25,000 --> 00:18:33,000
 My father and my mother have forsaken me, but the Lord will take me in."

269
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:35,000
 Does anyone notice -- I don't like grammar,

270
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:37,000
 but we're going to do a little bit of grammar.

271
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:38,000
 A little bit.

272
00:18:38,000 --> 00:18:39,000
 A tiny bit.

273
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:43,000
 Don't get me wrong, so teachers, please hold it till the end.

274
00:18:43,000 --> 00:18:49,000
 David speaks in all three tenses in this one section.

275
00:18:49,000 --> 00:18:53,000
 Hide not, turn not, cast not, forsake me not.

276
00:18:53,000 --> 00:18:55,000
 He's speaking in the present.

277
00:18:55,000 --> 00:18:57,000
 So in the moment, don't do this, God.

278
00:18:57,000 --> 00:18:58,000
 Don't do this.

279
00:18:58,000 --> 00:19:00,000
 Don't do this.

280
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:03,000
 The past tense, he says, "You who have been," the helping verb there,

281
00:19:03,000 --> 00:19:06,000
 "have been my help."

282
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:07,000
 Past tense.

283
00:19:07,000 --> 00:19:13,000
 Then the future, "But the Lord will take me in."

284
00:19:13,000 --> 00:19:17,000
 Why do you think he's giving us all three tenses?

285
00:19:17,000 --> 00:19:21,000
 Why isn't he just saying something about who God was or just his future hope

286
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:23,000
 about who God will be?

287
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:27,000
 Is he drawing out from his cry and his intimacy and the vulnerability

288
00:19:27,000 --> 00:19:28,000
 that he's found?

289
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:30,000
 David now prays in these three ways.

290
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:35,000
 The past of who God was, putting his trust there.

291
00:19:35,000 --> 00:19:39,000
 The present of who God is and the faith that he's going to have to have in this

292
00:19:39,000 --> 00:19:45,000
 moment and the future of who God will be.

293
00:19:45,000 --> 00:19:50,000
 David now has this profound sense of knowing God, right?

294
00:19:50,000 --> 00:19:56,000
 So seeking his face, now knowing him in all dimensions.

295
00:19:56,000 --> 00:20:04,000
 The intimacy part of his prayer revealed the countenance of who God was.

296
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:08,000
 And this is specifically important in our season of waiting because when we have

297
00:20:08,000 --> 00:20:15,000
 to wait for long periods, we forget.

298
00:20:15,000 --> 00:20:17,000
 The longer we wait, we forget.

299
00:20:17,000 --> 00:20:21,000
 And I think Andrew spoke about this either two weeks ago,

300
00:20:21,000 --> 00:20:26,000
 but understanding who God was is deeply important for us moving forward, right?

301
00:20:26,000 --> 00:20:32,000
 It's hard to have faith today if we don't have a reliable God from the past.

302
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:36,000
 And so David prays about who God was.

303
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:39,000
 He speaks about who God was.

304
00:20:39,000 --> 00:20:44,000
 Drawing on who God was had led David to this, remembering God correctly.

305
00:20:44,000 --> 00:20:46,000
 In the moments and the feelings, the longer we wait,

306
00:20:46,000 --> 00:20:49,000
 potentially our vision becomes skewed.

307
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:52,000
 Because of the stress and the anxiety of having to wait,

308
00:20:52,000 --> 00:20:57,000
 it's important that we remember correctly who God was.

309
00:20:57,000 --> 00:20:59,000
 In each line, his prayer gets stronger.

310
00:20:59,000 --> 00:21:04,000
 Because I know who he was, I now know who he is, and that produces faith in me.

311
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:06,000
 So he can say, "Cast me not off."

312
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:09,000
 He can say, "In this moment, God, don't do this.

313
00:21:09,000 --> 00:21:12,000
 Don't forsake me, God, because I know who you were back then."

314
00:21:12,000 --> 00:21:16,000
 It builds on one another, almost like a domino effect.

315
00:21:16,000 --> 00:21:21,000
 And from that, he can say, "I know that you will never leave me.

316
00:21:21,000 --> 00:21:25,000
 I know that in the future," and I love this example he gives here.

317
00:21:25,000 --> 00:21:30,000
 When your mother and your father forsake you, he's giving the most dramatic example

318
00:21:30,000 --> 00:21:32,000
 of a moment of need.

319
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:33,000
 Think about it.

320
00:21:33,000 --> 00:21:39,000
 In a culture that is so family-centered, if your mother and your father forsake you,

321
00:21:39,000 --> 00:21:40,000
 you have nothing.

322
00:21:40,000 --> 00:21:46,000
 David says that, "Even in my worst moment to come, because I know who God was,

323
00:21:46,000 --> 00:21:54,000
 because I stand on who he is today, I can have hope in the future for who he will be."

324
00:21:54,000 --> 00:21:58,000
 And that's why we have to be able to pray all three of these things,

325
00:21:58,000 --> 00:22:01,000
 understand all three of these tenses.

326
00:22:01,000 --> 00:22:05,000
 God is steadfast in his love, in his ways.

327
00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:06,000
 He's not changing.

328
00:22:06,000 --> 00:22:08,000
 He wasn't different yesterday.

329
00:22:08,000 --> 00:22:10,000
 He's going to be someone different today, be someone tomorrow.

330
00:22:10,000 --> 00:22:14,000
 There's a reason that the song that was written here says, "Hallelujah,

331
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:16,000
 praise the one who was.

332
00:22:16,000 --> 00:22:19,000
 Hallelujah, praise the one who is.

333
00:22:19,000 --> 00:22:20,000
 You'll forever be our God."

334
00:22:20,000 --> 00:22:23,000
 We love singing that, but have we thought about what that means?

335
00:22:23,000 --> 00:22:29,000
 We are declaring that based on who he was, we have faith in the moment for who he is,

336
00:22:29,000 --> 00:22:34,000
 and we have hope into who he will forever be.

337
00:22:34,000 --> 00:22:37,000
 That is what David is pulling out of these verses.

338
00:22:37,000 --> 00:22:40,000
 This is why he uses all three tenses.

339
00:22:40,000 --> 00:22:45,000
 God is not just our hope, but he is our dependable, reliable hope.

340
00:22:45,000 --> 00:22:49,000
 Because of what has happened in the past, I have confidence now,

341
00:22:49,000 --> 00:22:51,000
 and I have hope in the future.

342
00:22:51,000 --> 00:23:00,000
 It's a prophetic declaration that God is faithful, that all is not lost.

343
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:08,000
 Though I wait and he's not answered me yet, though I can't see an answer coming soon,

344
00:23:08,000 --> 00:23:12,000
 though nothing is breaking, God won't forsake me.

345
00:23:12,000 --> 00:23:19,000
 If my mother and my father, if the worst thing happens, God will be there for me.

346
00:23:19,000 --> 00:23:27,000
 To live in that prophetic hope is only possible when we allow our vulnerability,

347
00:23:27,000 --> 00:23:33,000
 our crying out to lead into intimacy, which allows us to know the face,

348
00:23:33,000 --> 00:23:37,000
 the attributes, the characteristics, the countenance of God.

349
00:23:37,000 --> 00:23:48,000
 It produces in us this three-dimensional hope and faith and confidence.

350
00:23:48,000 --> 00:23:52,000
 This is why waiting is a gift.

351
00:23:52,000 --> 00:23:54,000
 We've seen what it produces.

352
00:23:54,000 --> 00:23:58,000
 So far, it's produced intimacy, a chance to really know God,

353
00:23:58,000 --> 00:24:05,000
 a drawing in so that we can see and be near God who draws into the brokenhearted.

354
00:24:05,000 --> 00:24:08,000
 That's a gift.

355
00:24:08,000 --> 00:24:11,000
 And it produces this deep hope in us.

356
00:24:11,000 --> 00:24:13,000
 Hope is such an interesting thing.

357
00:24:13,000 --> 00:24:18,000
 We're just drawing in, and when things are--we're waiting for things to take place,

358
00:24:18,000 --> 00:24:19,000
 to have hope.

359
00:24:19,000 --> 00:24:21,000
 For some of us, it might be easier.

360
00:24:21,000 --> 00:24:24,000
 For others of us, it might be harder, right?

361
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:30,000
 Hope in God, I think scripture tells us, will not put us to shame in Romans 5:3.

362
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:34,000
 And I'm sure there are some of us here who are like, "Okay, cool.

363
00:24:34,000 --> 00:24:38,000
 I've been waiting, and hope has put me to shame.

364
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:42,000
 I've been waiting, and it's never happened."

365
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:44,000
 I'm not just doing this sermon series of waiting.

366
00:24:44,000 --> 00:24:48,000
 I've been waiting for years, and God hasn't come true.

367
00:24:48,000 --> 00:24:52,000
 So how do you say that, you know, if we just have hope and if we just believe

368
00:24:52,000 --> 00:24:58,000
 in all these big spiritual terms that it's going to be okay when God hasn't answered me,

369
00:24:58,000 --> 00:25:05,000
 when it still is hard, when we've been waiting for decades,

370
00:25:05,000 --> 00:25:09,000
 when our prayers have not been answered and we just live in this space

371
00:25:09,000 --> 00:25:17,000
 of disappointment, how can you ask me to have prophetic hope?

372
00:25:17,000 --> 00:25:20,000
 As I was writing this sermon, I got to this question,

373
00:25:20,000 --> 00:25:24,000
 and I almost skipped it because I'm like, "This is a hard thing to tackle.

374
00:25:24,000 --> 00:25:25,000
 This is not easy.

375
00:25:25,000 --> 00:25:29,000
 It's not a good preach to be like, 'Okay, but sometimes it doesn't work,' right?

376
00:25:29,000 --> 00:25:32,000
 Like, we all want to come to church and hear, 'Here are your four steps

377
00:25:32,000 --> 00:25:35,000
 or your three steps,' and then I'm going to go and do it and apply it,

378
00:25:35,000 --> 00:25:38,000
 and voila, hope is going to appear, and voila,

379
00:25:38,000 --> 00:25:40,000
 prayer is going to be answered.

380
00:25:40,000 --> 00:25:47,000
 But the very real reality is that we can cry out and be vulnerable.

381
00:25:47,000 --> 00:25:51,000
 We can express our dependency and reliance on the God who was,

382
00:25:51,000 --> 00:25:55,000
 who is, and who forever will be, or we can still be disappointed,

383
00:25:55,000 --> 00:25:59,000
 and our prayers can still not be answered as we think.

384
00:25:59,000 --> 00:26:05,000
 And how does God expect us to have hope and not live in a spiral

385
00:26:05,000 --> 00:26:12,000
 of disappointment when that happens?

386
00:26:12,000 --> 00:26:17,000
 The very last part of this passage addresses this in a very unique way.

387
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:20,000
 So I'm going to go ahead and say this is not going to answer it exactly,

388
00:26:20,000 --> 00:26:25,000
 but it's going to provide an answer that I hope will be good enough to get you

389
00:26:25,000 --> 00:26:29,000
 through the next day, okay?

390
00:26:29,000 --> 00:26:31,000
 Reading this last chunk, there are two particular things that we're going

391
00:26:31,000 --> 00:26:34,000
 to find in this last verse.

392
00:26:34,000 --> 00:26:38,000
 We're going to find something very interesting that David asks for,

393
00:26:38,000 --> 00:26:42,000
 and we're going to find an order of which he asks for these things.

394
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:45,000
 And I think both of these things, both of these components,

395
00:26:45,000 --> 00:26:51,000
 are crucial for us if we find ourselves waiting and it just hasn't happened yet,

396
00:26:51,000 --> 00:26:55,000
 and we're on the edge of spiraling into disappointment.

397
00:26:55,000 --> 00:26:59,000
 So let me just read you what he says in this last verse.

398
00:26:59,000 --> 00:27:02,000
 He says, "Teach me your way, O Lord."

399
00:27:02,000 --> 00:27:06,000
 Let's just stop there.

400
00:27:06,000 --> 00:27:08,000
 He says, "Teach me your way."

401
00:27:08,000 --> 00:27:10,000
 So he's cried out.

402
00:27:10,000 --> 00:27:12,000
 He's developed this intimacy.

403
00:27:12,000 --> 00:27:15,000
 He now has this faith and hope and confidence,

404
00:27:15,000 --> 00:27:19,000
 and he's this boldness to be able to come before God and now say what is on his

405
00:27:19,000 --> 00:27:22,000
 heart, not just how he feels, but perhaps what he wants.

406
00:27:22,000 --> 00:27:26,000
 And if I were David, after building up all of this,

407
00:27:26,000 --> 00:27:29,000
 my first thing would be like, "God, solve my problem now.

408
00:27:29,000 --> 00:27:31,000
 God, an answer, please.

409
00:27:31,000 --> 00:27:32,000
 I've been waiting.

410
00:27:32,000 --> 00:27:34,000
 Yes, I know you can do all things.

411
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:37,000
 I know who you were, who you are, who you will be.

412
00:27:37,000 --> 00:27:38,000
 I know your face.

413
00:27:38,000 --> 00:27:41,000
 Can you X, Y, Z?

414
00:27:41,000 --> 00:27:46,000
 Can you give me what it is that I need?"

415
00:27:46,000 --> 00:27:53,000
 Uniquely, what David does here is not that.

416
00:27:53,000 --> 00:27:58,000
 He says, "Teach me your way."

417
00:27:58,000 --> 00:28:02,000
 I really struggled with this one because if I'm honest, this is never my prayer.

418
00:28:02,000 --> 00:28:06,000
 In my waiting, when I'm on the edge of spiraling into disappointment,

419
00:28:06,000 --> 00:28:08,000
 my prayer is not, "God, teach me your ways."

420
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:11,000
 My prayer is, "God, help me escape.

421
00:28:11,000 --> 00:28:12,000
 God, get me out of this.

422
00:28:12,000 --> 00:28:15,000
 God, solve the problem.

423
00:28:15,000 --> 00:28:17,000
 God, show up, you know.

424
00:28:17,000 --> 00:28:20,000
 Holy Spirit, fire, fix the situation because I believe."

425
00:28:20,000 --> 00:28:26,000
 David, with all the belief, says, "God, teach me your way."

426
00:28:26,000 --> 00:28:28,000
 Why?

427
00:28:28,000 --> 00:28:32,000
 Why is that the request of all things to ask?

428
00:28:32,000 --> 00:28:38,000
 Why is that the request?

429
00:28:38,000 --> 00:28:45,000
 In modern terms, for some of us, it might be--our temptation would have been,

430
00:28:45,000 --> 00:28:47,000
 "God, take away the pain.

431
00:28:47,000 --> 00:28:49,000
 God, provide me the job.

432
00:28:49,000 --> 00:28:51,000
 God, bring my spouse."

433
00:28:51,000 --> 00:28:52,000
 Name it.

434
00:28:52,000 --> 00:28:56,000
 We all have the things that we're asking for, right?

435
00:28:56,000 --> 00:28:58,000
 God, do this.

436
00:28:58,000 --> 00:29:01,000
 David says, "Teach me your ways."

437
00:29:01,000 --> 00:29:06,000
 With prophetic hope, he asks for God to teach him his way.

438
00:29:06,000 --> 00:29:11,000
 See, David has an understanding here that's very different than I think we

439
00:29:11,000 --> 00:29:14,000
 would normally carry.

440
00:29:14,000 --> 00:29:18,000
 David's prayer and petition has caused him to know God better.

441
00:29:18,000 --> 00:29:23,000
 And in that knowing of God better, in that seeing God's face,

442
00:29:23,000 --> 00:29:25,000
 something has shifted.

443
00:29:25,000 --> 00:29:30,000
 David's still in a messy situation, but his desire is now to know God's way,

444
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:32,000
 not to get a solution.

445
00:29:32,000 --> 00:29:35,000
 "Teach me your ways," the first thing he asks.

446
00:29:35,000 --> 00:29:41,000
 As God has drawn him in, in the intimacy that's been produced,

447
00:29:41,000 --> 00:29:46,000
 his desires have now been reprioritized.

448
00:29:46,000 --> 00:29:48,000
 Very subtle shift.

449
00:29:48,000 --> 00:29:53,000
 Situation's still the same, but the first thing he asks,

450
00:29:53,000 --> 00:29:58,000
 the first thing he asks is that God would teach him his ways.

451
00:29:58,000 --> 00:30:05,000
 So I am convinced that we cannot draw close to God and see him more clearly

452
00:30:05,000 --> 00:30:13,000
 for who he truly is and want anything other than to be more like him.

453
00:30:13,000 --> 00:30:16,000
 This is not an easy preach.

454
00:30:16,000 --> 00:30:22,000
 Even in the middle of the waiting, I am convinced that when we draw into

455
00:30:22,000 --> 00:30:29,000
 God and we allow him to draw near to us, when he shows us who he truly is,

456
00:30:29,000 --> 00:30:37,000
 something changes in us, that what we desire more is to be like him.

457
00:30:37,000 --> 00:30:44,000
 Even though our situation hasn't changed yet, David desires this.

458
00:30:44,000 --> 00:30:49,000
 It's like he seeks formation more than the solution.

459
00:30:49,000 --> 00:30:53,000
 We have this appetite after we've seen the countenance of God.

460
00:30:53,000 --> 00:30:57,000
 Now that we've come close to God and we see who he really is, his ways,

461
00:30:57,000 --> 00:31:03,000
 his methods, we're like, "God, help me to see it the way you see it.

462
00:31:03,000 --> 00:31:08,000
 Help me to think about these things the way you think about these things.

463
00:31:08,000 --> 00:31:13,000
 It's not easy, but God, help me to have your perspective on this.

464
00:31:13,000 --> 00:31:14,000
 I want to be like you.

465
00:31:14,000 --> 00:31:16,000
 Lead me in your ways.

466
00:31:16,000 --> 00:31:17,000
 Give me your approach.

467
00:31:17,000 --> 00:31:24,000
 I want to feel about this, God, the way that you feel about this.

468
00:31:24,000 --> 00:31:29,000
 Make me more like you, God, so that I can do this right."

469
00:31:29,000 --> 00:31:32,000
 That's what David is saying here.

470
00:31:32,000 --> 00:31:35,000
 And it's not the pendulum swinging to the opposite end because he's prayed,

471
00:31:35,000 --> 00:31:38,000
 he's super spiritual, so now he no longer wants anything.

472
00:31:38,000 --> 00:31:41,000
 But, again, I said what he asked for and the order.

473
00:31:41,000 --> 00:31:46,000
 The first thing he asked for, yes, is for God to make him more like him,

474
00:31:46,000 --> 00:31:49,000
 for him to see God's ways, follow God's ways.

475
00:31:49,000 --> 00:31:51,000
 And then he makes his request, right?

476
00:31:51,000 --> 00:31:54,000
 So we can look and see.

477
00:31:54,000 --> 00:31:57,000
 Sorry, we're going to skip to the next slide, team.

478
00:31:57,000 --> 00:32:00,000
 It says, "Give me not up to the will of my adversaries,

479
00:32:00,000 --> 00:32:02,000
 for false witness have arisen against me."

480
00:32:02,000 --> 00:32:09,000
 First he starts with, "God, teach me to see things like you.

481
00:32:09,000 --> 00:32:14,000
 And then, God, help me because this is hard and my adversaries are around,

482
00:32:14,000 --> 00:32:16,000
 so don't give me up to the will of them."

483
00:32:16,000 --> 00:32:19,000
 But first he says, "Help me to see things like you.

484
00:32:19,000 --> 00:32:21,000
 Teach me your ways."

485
00:32:21,000 --> 00:32:27,000
 It reminds me of when Jesus is on the earth and his disciples are following him

486
00:32:27,000 --> 00:32:29,000
 for years and they're like, "We don't even know how to pray."

487
00:32:29,000 --> 00:32:31,000
 Jesus says, "Let me teach you how to pray."

488
00:32:31,000 --> 00:32:33,000
 When you pray, you say, "Our Father who art in heaven,

489
00:32:33,000 --> 00:32:34,000
 hallowed be your name."

490
00:32:34,000 --> 00:32:40,000
 First thing you say is, "Your kingdom come, your will be done," right?

491
00:32:40,000 --> 00:32:44,000
 He doesn't stop there though because after that, two lines later,

492
00:32:44,000 --> 00:32:48,000
 "Give us today, God, I need, I still have needs,

493
00:32:48,000 --> 00:32:53,000
 but first I submit to your kingdom come, your will be done."

494
00:32:53,000 --> 00:32:55,000
 That's exactly what David is doing here.

495
00:32:55,000 --> 00:32:59,000
 "Teach me your ways, O Lord.

496
00:32:59,000 --> 00:33:05,000
 This is my situation, but God, teach me to see it and to feel it like you do.

497
00:33:05,000 --> 00:33:07,000
 Teach me to approach it like you do."

498
00:33:07,000 --> 00:33:12,000
 God makes room for our wants and our needs and our prayer,

499
00:33:12,000 --> 00:33:17,000
 but when we draw near to him, we will find that our desires are reprioritized,

500
00:33:17,000 --> 00:33:21,000
 that they are reordered into a more healthy, more long-term,

501
00:33:21,000 --> 00:33:24,000
 bigger picture perspective.

502
00:33:24,000 --> 00:33:26,000
 All of this takes place in prayer.

503
00:33:26,000 --> 00:33:31,000
 And what that makes me realize is that we should probably pray more, right?

504
00:33:31,000 --> 00:33:34,000
 Like all of this is a byproduct of just crying out to God,

505
00:33:34,000 --> 00:33:40,000
 like the domino effect of all of this, hope and faith and confidence,

506
00:33:40,000 --> 00:33:43,000
 reprioritizing my desires.

507
00:33:43,000 --> 00:33:45,000
 I mean, I try to reprioritize my desires all the time.

508
00:33:45,000 --> 00:33:46,000
 I'm terrible at it.

509
00:33:46,000 --> 00:33:51,000
 But if I spend time with God and I come close to him, he can do that.

510
00:33:51,000 --> 00:33:52,000
 That's on the table for us.

511
00:33:52,000 --> 00:33:57,000
 When I think about this being the reality, my response is we should pray more.

512
00:33:57,000 --> 00:34:02,000
 We should really be into prayer for what it does.

513
00:34:02,000 --> 00:34:04,000
 Prayer is a gift.

514
00:34:04,000 --> 00:34:08,000
 Waiting is a gift because if we wait well, we will pray.

515
00:34:08,000 --> 00:34:11,000
 And when we pray, he'll be close.

516
00:34:11,000 --> 00:34:12,000
 He will hear.

517
00:34:12,000 --> 00:34:14,000
 He will transform.

518
00:34:14,000 --> 00:34:15,000
 He will comfort.

519
00:34:15,000 --> 00:34:18,000
 He will be near when we're brokenhearted.

520
00:34:18,000 --> 00:34:21,000
 It's an invitation to prayer.

521
00:34:21,000 --> 00:34:25,000
 That's why waiting is a gift.

522
00:34:25,000 --> 00:34:26,000
 So let me wrap this up.

523
00:34:26,000 --> 00:34:30,000
 Normally, I like to say that as a good preacher, I have three takeaway points for you.

524
00:34:30,000 --> 00:34:32,000
 But today, I only have two, okay?

525
00:34:32,000 --> 00:34:33,000
 Two things.

526
00:34:33,000 --> 00:34:36,000
 First thing is this.

527
00:34:36,000 --> 00:34:38,000
 Takeaway point number one, come to God.

528
00:34:38,000 --> 00:34:40,000
 Just come to him.

529
00:34:40,000 --> 00:34:42,000
 Nothing deep, nothing fancy.

530
00:34:42,000 --> 00:34:43,000
 Come to God.

531
00:34:43,000 --> 00:34:49,000
 Sometimes as Christians, it's too quick that we regurgitate the things that we know.

532
00:34:49,000 --> 00:34:56,000
 We regurgitate good theology or something quotable from Instagram or whatever someone else said.

533
00:34:56,000 --> 00:34:59,000
 But we do that in place of actually going to God.

534
00:34:59,000 --> 00:35:00,000
 Let me confess.

535
00:35:00,000 --> 00:35:03,000
 So this has been one of the worst weeks for me and my family.

536
00:35:03,000 --> 00:35:06,000
 Just everything that can go wrong keeps going wrong.

537
00:35:06,000 --> 00:35:11,000
 Last week, my son was sick and then my wife and then me and then my -- we're all sick.

538
00:35:11,000 --> 00:35:13,000
 Everyone's just sick in my house.

539
00:35:13,000 --> 00:35:21,000
 But while my son was sick, it went from like the stomach bug for a couple of days, which is just the worst thing ever for like a 4-year-old.

540
00:35:21,000 --> 00:35:23,000
 And I have to, like, quarantine with him in the room.

541
00:35:23,000 --> 00:35:26,000
 So it's me and Elias just can be living with the stomach bugs.

542
00:35:26,000 --> 00:35:27,000
 That's why I wasn't here last week.

543
00:35:27,000 --> 00:35:32,000
 And then, like, by the time the stomach bug was gone, Elias started sweating a fever.

544
00:35:32,000 --> 00:35:33,000
 It was, like, great.

545
00:35:33,000 --> 00:35:35,000
 So we go to the doctor on Monday.

546
00:35:35,000 --> 00:35:36,000
 My wife takes him in.

547
00:35:36,000 --> 00:35:39,000
 And he has not RSV, some other acronym.

548
00:35:39,000 --> 00:35:42,000
 And if it's ever an acronym, you know something's wrong, right?

549
00:35:42,000 --> 00:35:43,000
 It doesn't tell you the words.

550
00:35:43,000 --> 00:35:46,000
 It's just a couple of letters, you know, something's really off.

551
00:35:46,000 --> 00:35:47,000
 He has that, and then we test it.

552
00:35:47,000 --> 00:35:48,000
 My daughter has that.

553
00:35:48,000 --> 00:35:49,000
 I'm just like, great.

554
00:35:49,000 --> 00:35:51,000
 My 1-year-old, my 4-year-old are sick.

555
00:35:51,000 --> 00:35:55,000
 Great time in life.

556
00:35:55,000 --> 00:35:59,000
 I, talking to my wife, I'm the optimistic one in our relationship.

557
00:35:59,000 --> 00:36:01,000
 I like to think it's all going to be okay.

558
00:36:01,000 --> 00:36:03,000
 I'm always like, yeah, it's fine.

559
00:36:03,000 --> 00:36:04,000
 God's got us.

560
00:36:04,000 --> 00:36:05,000
 It's okay.

561
00:36:05,000 --> 00:36:06,000
 So she's worried.

562
00:36:06,000 --> 00:36:07,000
 She's stressed.

563
00:36:07,000 --> 00:36:08,000
 I'm like, no, no, no, it's okay.

564
00:36:08,000 --> 00:36:09,000
 It's just some virus.

565
00:36:09,000 --> 00:36:10,000
 It'll be fine.

566
00:36:10,000 --> 00:36:11,000
 No big deal.

567
00:36:11,000 --> 00:36:13,000
 You know, God's been there for me before.

568
00:36:13,000 --> 00:36:15,000
 He didn't bring me this far to let me down.

569
00:36:15,000 --> 00:36:16,000
 God's going to be with me.

570
00:36:16,000 --> 00:36:19,000
 He doesn't teach you to swim to let you drown, is what my grandmother told me.

571
00:36:19,000 --> 00:36:22,000
 So I'm just telling that to myself and to my wife and to my kids,

572
00:36:22,000 --> 00:36:26,000
 and I'm just speaking all the things that I know.

573
00:36:26,000 --> 00:36:30,000
 And then my parents, who are in the States, call.

574
00:36:30,000 --> 00:36:32,000
 I grew up with my parents as pastors.

575
00:36:32,000 --> 00:36:33,000
 My dad's a pastor.

576
00:36:33,000 --> 00:36:36,000
 My mom, a worship leader, grew up very Christian.

577
00:36:36,000 --> 00:36:38,000
 So my parents call, and they're like, oh, what's wrong?

578
00:36:38,000 --> 00:36:40,000
 I'm like, oh, Elias is sick, yada, yada, yada.

579
00:36:40,000 --> 00:36:43,000
 It's okay because God is for us and all the things.

580
00:36:43,000 --> 00:36:50,000
 And my parents, in their good African Pentecostal way, just start praying.

581
00:36:50,000 --> 00:36:57,000
 On FaceTime, they just start pleading the blood of Jesus over my 4-year-old son

582
00:36:57,000 --> 00:37:02,000
 that no weapon formed against him would -- and they just start leaning into prayer,

583
00:37:02,000 --> 00:37:04,000
 like hardcore prayer meeting.

584
00:37:04,000 --> 00:37:07,000
 I mean, we have dodgy Wi-Fi, so it's breaking in and out, and it's like,

585
00:37:07,000 --> 00:37:09,000
 are they speaking in tongues or are they speaking in English?

586
00:37:09,000 --> 00:37:14,000
 We don't know, but they are praying hard.

587
00:37:14,000 --> 00:37:17,000
 I mean, they are leaning in, like so much so that my son -- I mean, he's 4,

588
00:37:17,000 --> 00:37:20,000
 and he has a fever, so he just, like, gets up and walks off.

589
00:37:20,000 --> 00:37:21,000
 And they keep praying.

590
00:37:21,000 --> 00:37:24,000
 Like, it's just that they were committed to it.

591
00:37:24,000 --> 00:37:27,000
 I get off the phone, and I realize, check my spirit.

592
00:37:27,000 --> 00:37:32,000
 Right before I wrote this sermon, God was like, you never prayed for your son.

593
00:37:32,000 --> 00:37:36,000
 You had all the theology to calm your nerves.

594
00:37:36,000 --> 00:37:40,000
 You had all the right things to say to help yourself not be anxious.

595
00:37:40,000 --> 00:37:46,000
 But you didn't once draw near to me.

596
00:37:46,000 --> 00:37:55,000
 Sometimes it's very easy for us to over-Christianize the moment

597
00:37:55,000 --> 00:38:02,000
 and miss out on the gift that comes when we actually just pray.

598
00:38:02,000 --> 00:38:11,000
 And so, as simple as it is, pray. Don't just talk about God. Talk to God.

599
00:38:11,000 --> 00:38:17,000
 And secondly, in that space, on the same point, we have to dispel this lie

600
00:38:17,000 --> 00:38:22,000
 that holds us back from intimacy, that God doesn't -- this idea that we think

601
00:38:22,000 --> 00:38:25,000
 we have to have it all put together when we come to God.

602
00:38:25,000 --> 00:38:28,000
 God doesn't need your Christianese.

603
00:38:28,000 --> 00:38:31,000
 God doesn't need your jargon.

604
00:38:31,000 --> 00:38:35,000
 God doesn't need you put together to come to Him.

605
00:38:35,000 --> 00:38:38,000
 It's not your job to put yourself together.

606
00:38:38,000 --> 00:38:43,000
 Just come to Him. So nothing disqualifies you from praying.

607
00:38:43,000 --> 00:38:48,000
 If you're hurt, and if your heart's broken, and you're on the edge of spiraling,

608
00:38:48,000 --> 00:38:52,000
 you're in a great position to pray. You're qualified. Thumbs up.

609
00:38:52,000 --> 00:38:59,000
 You can approach Him, and you know that He draws near to those who are brokenhearted.

610
00:38:59,000 --> 00:39:04,000
 And so to make it very simple, here is a quick little guide for us.

611
00:39:04,000 --> 00:39:06,000
 When you pray this week, try it like this.

612
00:39:06,000 --> 00:39:11,000
 God, I feel -- we're talking about crying out and being honest with Him.

613
00:39:11,000 --> 00:39:18,000
 God, I feel angry, sad, frustrated, lost, livid, disappointed, can't handle it.

614
00:39:18,000 --> 00:39:23,000
 God, I feel -- and just tell Him.

615
00:39:23,000 --> 00:39:27,000
 You fill in the blank with what's best for you.

616
00:39:27,000 --> 00:39:31,000
 And follow that with this, God, I fear.

617
00:39:31,000 --> 00:39:35,000
 God's not afraid of you telling Him what you're afraid of, okay?

618
00:39:35,000 --> 00:39:38,000
 God, I feel this. God, I fear that it's never going to happen,

619
00:39:38,000 --> 00:39:40,000
 that I'm going to be left alone, that this is going to fail,

620
00:39:40,000 --> 00:39:43,000
 that I'm going to pray, and I'm not going to get anything back.

621
00:39:43,000 --> 00:39:50,000
 You fill in the blank, but go to God, okay?

622
00:39:50,000 --> 00:39:55,000
 Second point, check your hope.

623
00:39:55,000 --> 00:39:58,000
 Where is your hope when you're waiting?

624
00:39:58,000 --> 00:40:02,000
 If hope is only found as a result of intimacy in God,

625
00:40:02,000 --> 00:40:07,000
 then true hope in Jesus only comes from being with Jesus.

626
00:40:07,000 --> 00:40:11,000
 Where is your hope?

627
00:40:11,000 --> 00:40:16,000
 We don't want a fake hope that's not dependable or not reliable.

628
00:40:16,000 --> 00:40:18,000
 We don't need a hope that has an expiration date.

629
00:40:18,000 --> 00:40:25,000
 That's why we can be confident in God, who is our hope because of what He's done,

630
00:40:25,000 --> 00:40:27,000
 what He's doing, and what He will do.

631
00:40:27,000 --> 00:40:32,000
 That's why I harked on that point for so long, hope that's actually reliable.

632
00:40:32,000 --> 00:40:34,000
 This is the hope that we find in Jesus.

633
00:40:34,000 --> 00:40:39,000
 So when our hope is failing, consider where exactly is your hope?

634
00:40:39,000 --> 00:40:45,000
 God doesn't change. He's consistent, steadfast, constant, never-ending.

635
00:40:45,000 --> 00:40:49,000
 Find the synonym you want. He's always there.

636
00:40:49,000 --> 00:40:50,000
 Where is your hope?

637
00:40:50,000 --> 00:40:55,000
 Let the intimacy found in crying out in your vulnerability to God,

638
00:40:55,000 --> 00:40:58,000
 let it lead you to seek His face,

639
00:40:58,000 --> 00:41:03,000
 and let the hope that He wants for you to have be found.

640
00:41:03,000 --> 00:41:06,000
 And so for those of us who are in that space, who need to check our hope,

641
00:41:06,000 --> 00:41:09,000
 two prayer prompts for you as well.

642
00:41:09,000 --> 00:41:12,000
 God, you are.

643
00:41:12,000 --> 00:41:16,000
 And this is not you talking about God. This is you talking to God.

644
00:41:16,000 --> 00:41:19,000
 God, you are for me.

645
00:41:19,000 --> 00:41:21,000
 You are patient. You are kind.

646
00:41:21,000 --> 00:41:22,000
 You are able.

647
00:41:22,000 --> 00:41:27,000
 You are whatever the attribute of God is that you need to hold on to.

648
00:41:27,000 --> 00:41:30,000
 Tell Him that.

649
00:41:30,000 --> 00:41:32,000
 And then this last one, this is quite important.

650
00:41:32,000 --> 00:41:34,000
 Make sure you don't skip this part.

651
00:41:34,000 --> 00:41:39,000
 God, help me build my hope on you because you are, okay?

652
00:41:39,000 --> 00:41:42,000
 We're not just saying what He is.

653
00:41:42,000 --> 00:41:48,000
 We're asking Him to help our hope be built upon Him because of who He is.

654
00:41:48,000 --> 00:41:51,000
 God wants to meet us in our waiting.

655
00:41:51,000 --> 00:41:55,000
 God has gifts for us as we draw in and as we pray.

656
00:41:55,000 --> 00:42:00,000
 So as the worship team comes, can I just get you to close your eyes?

657
00:42:00,000 --> 00:42:13,000
 And pray for us before we enter into our time of response.

658
00:42:13,000 --> 00:42:19,000
 Something we do here at the Vine very often, but if you find yourself in a season of waiting,

659
00:42:19,000 --> 00:42:26,000
 in a season of needing to hear from God, or maybe you're on the edge of frustration,

660
00:42:26,000 --> 00:42:31,000
 if you find yourself needing to come back to God, to actually pray to Him,

661
00:42:31,000 --> 00:42:33,000
 you need to find yourself checking your hope.

662
00:42:33,000 --> 00:42:37,000
 Can I just ask you to open your hands wherever you are?

663
00:42:37,000 --> 00:42:46,000
 And we're just going to do this as a posture of our openness to Him in this moment.

664
00:42:46,000 --> 00:42:57,000
 God, we thank you that you don't disappear, that you don't leave us,

665
00:42:57,000 --> 00:43:03,000
 that you are not far away in these seasons of prolonged waiting.

666
00:43:03,000 --> 00:43:11,000
 God, we thank you that waiting is an invitation to greater intimacy with you through prayer.

667
00:43:11,000 --> 00:43:17,000
 And we thank you that as we come to you, as we draw near to you, you draw near to us as well.

668
00:43:17,000 --> 00:43:23,000
 So God, for those of us who are in need of the comfort that comes from drawing near to you,

669
00:43:23,000 --> 00:43:27,000
 would you speak to our hearts now?

670
00:43:27,000 --> 00:43:33,000
 Would your Holy Spirit impress upon our hearts that it's okay to be vulnerable before you,

671
00:43:33,000 --> 00:43:41,000
 that it's okay to bear our hearts to you, to tell you what it feels like,

672
00:43:41,000 --> 00:43:47,000
 to express our sadness, our disappointment, our grief?

673
00:43:47,000 --> 00:43:53,000
 And Holy Spirit, would you remind us that God is big enough to handle that,

674
00:43:53,000 --> 00:43:58,000
 that He's a comforter, He's not just going to hear it and dismiss it,

675
00:43:58,000 --> 00:44:02,000
 but He's going to draw near to us.

676
00:44:02,000 --> 00:44:06,000
 God, I pray that those of us in this room now would, as we draw near,

677
00:44:06,000 --> 00:44:12,000
 that we would seek your face, God, that you are not hiding from us,

678
00:44:12,000 --> 00:44:18,000
 but that as we seek your face that you will be found, that you will be known,

679
00:44:18,000 --> 00:44:24,000
 and that as we know you and see you and seek you, hope will be built in our hearts, God.

680
00:44:24,000 --> 00:44:29,000
 Hope built on the fact that who you were is reliable and consistent,

681
00:44:29,000 --> 00:44:32,000
 who you are now is still for us,

682
00:44:32,000 --> 00:44:37,000
 and we can live with this prophetic hope of who you will be in the future.

683
00:44:37,000 --> 00:44:40,000
 And God, I pray that as we come to you in this space,

684
00:44:40,000 --> 00:44:43,000
 would you do for us what we cannot do for ourselves.

685
00:44:43,000 --> 00:44:49,000
 While we may seek solutions, God, would you reprioritize our desires to seek formation,

686
00:44:49,000 --> 00:44:55,000
 to be made more like you, God, to want the things of you, to see things your way.

687
00:44:55,000 --> 00:44:58,000
 Give us a gift that's bigger than the solving of a problem today,

688
00:44:58,000 --> 00:45:03,000
 but something also for tomorrow.

689
00:45:03,000 --> 00:45:08,000
 God, we come to you because we know who you are.

690
00:45:08,000 --> 00:45:11,000
 Would you remind us of that Holy Spirit?

691
00:45:11,000 --> 00:45:16,000
 You speak to us where we need, and we surrender and give these things to you.

692
00:45:16,000 --> 00:45:30,000
 In Jesus' name, Amen.

